{"_id":"67ad5e50-b501-11e8-a1b7-df997e15fc27","postId":"2012_02_reporting-progress-from-async-tasks-af25e7ab-e6be-3f73-91cc-c2684fafe888","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2012/02/reporting-progress-from-async-tasks.html","replyTo":"9c3f3860-b4fb-11e8-a1b7-df997e15fc27","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"I never did write a blog post followup on this.\r\n\r\nThe general idea is that to prevent \"spurious\" progress updates, you'll need some sort of unsubscription mechanism. This can be done yourself, or you can use Rx, something like this: https://gist.github.com/StephenCleary/4248e50b4cb52b933c0d\r\n\r\nThe usage is always awkward, though, since the consumer must unsubscribe.","date":"2018-09-10T13:57:07.822Z"}